        <section class="prose mt-8">
          <h2>How this tire size calculator works</h2>
          <p>
            Passenger and light truck tires are usually described in either
            <strong>P-metric</strong> format (e.g. <code>225/65R17</code>) or
            <strong>flotation</strong> format (e.g. <code>31x10.50R15</code>).
            This tool understands both, converts them into physical dimensions,
            and compares your current and new tire.
          </p>

          <h3>P-metric tire size formula</h3>
          <p>A P-metric size looks like <code>225/65R17</code>:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>225</strong> – section width in millimeters</li>
            <li><strong>65</strong> – aspect ratio (sidewall height is 65% of width)</li>
            <li><strong>R</strong> – radial construction</li>
            <li><strong>17</strong> – rim diameter in inches</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="formula-box text-sm">
            <p><strong>Sidewall height</strong> (mm):</p>
            <p>\(\text{sidewall} = \text{width} \times \frac{\text{aspect}}{100}\)</p>
            <p class="mt-2"><strong>Overall diameter</strong> (mm):</p>
            <p>\(\text{diameter} = 2 \times \text{sidewall} + \text{rim} \times 25.4\)</p>
            <p class="mt-2"><strong>Circumference</strong> (mm):</p>
            <p>\(\text{circumference} = \pi \times \text{diameter}\)</p>
            <p class="mt-2"><strong>Revolutions per mile</strong>:</p>
            <p>\(\text{revs/mile} = \dfrac{25\,400 \times 1000}{\text{circumference (mm)}}\)</p>
          </div>

          <h3>Flotation tire size formula</h3>
          <p>
            A flotation size looks like <code>31x10.50R15</code>:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>31</strong> – overall diameter in inches</li>
            <li><strong>10.50</strong> – section width in inches</li>
            <li><strong>R</strong> – radial construction</li>
            <li><strong>15</strong> – rim diameter in inches</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="formula-box text-sm">
            <p><strong>Overall diameter</strong> (mm):</p>
            <p>\(\text{diameter} = \text{diameter (in)} \times 25.4\)</p>
            <p class="mt-2"><strong>Section width</strong> (mm):</p>
            <p>\(\text{width} = \text{width (in)} \times 25.4\)</p>
            <p class="mt-2"><strong>Sidewall height</strong> (mm):</p>
            <p>\(\text{sidewall} = \dfrac{\text{diameter (mm)} - \text{rim (in)} \times 25.4}{2}\)</p>
          </div>

          <h2>Interpreting the results</h2>
          <h3>Diameter difference and fitment</h3>
          <p>
            The <strong>overall diameter</strong> is the most important number when
            changing tire size. It affects:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Speedometer and odometer accuracy</li>
            <li>Effective gearing (acceleration vs. cruising RPM)</li>
            <li>Clearance in the wheel wells and against suspension components</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            A common rule of thumb is to keep diameter within about
            <strong>±3%</strong> of the original size. This calculator highlights
            when you are outside that range so you know to double‑check
            clearance and legal limits.
          </p>

          <h3>Width and sidewall changes</h3>
          <p>
            Increasing <strong>width</strong> can improve grip but may cause rubbing
            on fenders, liners, or suspension arms if there is not enough space.
            A taller <strong>sidewall</strong> usually gives a softer ride and more
            protection off‑road, while a shorter sidewall sharpens steering but
            is more vulnerable to pothole damage.
          </p>

          <h3>Speedometer error</h3>
          <p>
            Your speedometer assumes a specific tire circumference. If the new
            tire is larger, you travel <em>farther</em> per revolution:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>New diameter larger → actual speed higher than indicated</li>
            <li>New diameter smaller → actual speed lower than indicated</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            The calculator shows the actual speed at a chosen indicated speed
            (e.g. 60 mph) and the percentage error so you can judge whether the
            change is acceptable.
          </p>

          <h2>Practical tips when changing tire size</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Always check wheel width and offset – they must be compatible with the new tire width.</li>
            <li>Turn the steering from lock to lock and compress the suspension to check for rubbing.</li>
            <li>Remember that very large diameter changes can affect ABS, traction control, and stability systems.</li>
            <li>Consult your vehicle manual or a professional installer before deviating significantly from OEM sizes.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <section class="mt-8" id="faq">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Tire size FAQ</h2>
          <div class="space-y-3">
            <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
              <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">How do I read tire size numbers like 225/45R17?</summary>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                225/45R17 means: 225 mm section width, 45% aspect ratio (sidewall
                height is 45% of 225 mm), R for radial construction, and 17 inch
                wheel diameter. Load index and speed rating follow, e.g. 94W.
              </p>
            </details>
            <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
              <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">How much can I change tire size without problems?</summary>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                Most installers recommend keeping overall diameter within about
                ±3% of the original tire size. Larger changes can affect ABS,
                traction control, gearing, speedometer accuracy, and clearance.
              </p>
            </details>
            <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
              <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">Will a different tire size affect my speedometer?</summary>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                Yes. If the new tire has a larger diameter, you will travel
                faster than your speedometer indicates. If the diameter is
                smaller, you will travel slower. Use the speedometer section of
                this calculator to see the exact error at a chosen speed.
              </p>
            </details>
            <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
              <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">Can I switch between metric and flotation tire sizes?</summary>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                Yes. This calculator supports both P-metric sizes (e.g.,
                225/65R17) and flotation sizes (e.g., 33x12.50R17). It converts
                both to the same set of dimensions so you can compare them
                directly.
              </p>
            </details>
            <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
              <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">Do I need to change wheels when changing tire size?</summary>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                It depends. If the new tire uses a different rim diameter (e.g.,
                moving from 17&quot; to 18&quot;), you must change wheels. Even with the
                same rim diameter, you must ensure the wheel width and offset
                are suitable for the new tire width and that there is enough
                clearance in the wheel wells.
              </p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </section>
